<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="2cce9146-6a73-5af4-91eb-791f704369ad" activityNameId="06ffc039-f73b-440c-a5a0-8dc7393a5e71" parentActivityId="673f44d9-d0dd-51f0-8238-6ba217790c10" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">concrete block production</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts with the reception of raw materials at the concrete block production site.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of concrete block. The dataset includes the reception of materials, dosing and mixing, block production by vibration, curing and storage, as well as internal transports. The dataset does not include the packaging. Only discarded blocks and waste wood are taken into account as solid waste. </includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset describes the production of mixed blocks of concrete in the warm climate zone of Santa Isabel, Ecuador. The blocks have a characteristic compressive strength of 3.1 - 3.45 MPa and are mainly used in non-structural masonry walls. The produced blocks weigh approximately 5.4 kg and the most common dimensions are of (10 x 40 x 20) cm (width, length, height). Data comes from measurement and information provided in the factory visited in March 2022 ("HormiOrtiz"). The dataset includes the whole manufacturing process of the blocks. It does not include administration and infrastructure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">This dataset was developed by Estefania Barros, Kristi Padrón, Jonnathan Aguirre and Juan Sebastian Martines, under the supervision of Prof. Dolores Sucozhañay and Prof. Paul Vanegas, from the Inclusive Circular Economy and Sustainable Development Research Group of the University of Cuenca (ECI) in the frame of the CEELA (Strengthening capacities for energy efficiency in buildings in Latin America) project with the support of the Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC).</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="27f6acbc-2350-450e-9762-1ce00e12ecba">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2395:Manufacture of articles of concrete, cement and plaster</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0d0e72a0-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">EC</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of concrete blocks representative for Ecuador. Data comes from primary data collection in Ecuador.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Current production technology. The dataset covers the main technologies for concrete block production in Ecuador. The manufacturing process begins by dosing and mixing the cement, aggregates and water. In the block machine, the steel cast is filled with the mix and the block is shaped and compacted by vibration. The fresh block is then transported to a place where the drying/curing process begins. The cure is done by spraying water over the blocks in order to ensure proper hydration of the cement and avoid that the blocks get "burned". The spraying is done for three days, three times per day. The blocks are then packed in pallets and stored.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2022-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period is from 2022 (year of data collection) to 2023 (year of dataset compilation).</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
